    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-07-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-07-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="90"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d90">
                <head>90. Memorandum for the Record<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d90fn1">Source:
                        National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential
                        Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 1327, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Unfiled Material, 1971, 5 of 12. Secret;
                            <gloss target="#t_NODIS1">Nodis</gloss>. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SHH1">Harold Saunders</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New Delhi</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-07-06">July 6, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Description of <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>–<persName
                            corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> Talk</item>
                </list>
                <p>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> met alone with Prime
                    Minister <persName corresp="#p_GI1">Gandhi</persName>ʼs personal secretary,
                        <persName corresp="#p_HPN1">P.N. Haksar</persName>, at 6:00 p.m. July 6 in
                    New Delhi. The following represents Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName>ʼs brief description of the conversation after he
                    returned to the Ashoka Hotel.</p>
                <p>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> said he had calmed <persName
                        corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> down. <persName corresp="#p_HPN1"
                        >Haksar</persName> had started critical comments of the <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">US</gloss> policy on arms assistance to Pakistan. Dr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> said he had told <persName
                        corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> that if India were going into a paroxysm
                    over this there was no way in which the <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> could
                    respond. If the Indians could quiet down, the <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                    would try to work quietly over the next few months to encourage a settlement of
                    the refugee problem. Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> said
                    that <persName corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> conceded that the <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">US</gloss> could not respond to a public furor. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> said that the government of India had a
                    problem: It did not want to go to war but it did not know how not to go to
                    war.</p>
                <p>Later, Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> recalled that he had
                    told <persName corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> that he thought the Indians
                    were just making a lot of noise in order to set up <pb facs="0250" n="221"
                        xml:id="pg_221"/> an invasion of East Pakistan. He said that he had
                    suggested that he and <persName corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> talk about
                    “ways not to have a war.”</p>
                <p>After further conversation with <persName corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> and
                    Foreign Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KTN1">Kaul</persName>, at dinner, Dr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> said his assumption is that
                    they are playing power politics with cold calculations. This is quite different
                    from the embassyʼs assumption that this is a genuine Indian feeling against our
                    arms aid to Pakistan. He said that he had told <persName corresp="#p_HPN1"
                        >Haksar</persName> that “we are men of the world.” <persName
                        corresp="#p_HPN1">Haksar</persName> knows that aid does not make the
                    difference. Even if the <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> shipped all $29
                    million worth of military equipment, it would not make any difference in the
                    situation. So letʼs stop yelling about something that does not make a difference
                    and talk might.</p>
            </div>
